 heavy fall of snow in the neighbourhood of Exeter and the south of Devon. On the following morning the inhabitants of the above towns were surprised at discovering the track of some strange and mysterious animal, endowed with the power of ubiquity, as the footprints were to be seen in all kinds of inaccessable places-on the tops of houses and narrow walls, in gardens and courtyards enclosed by high walls and palings, as well as in open fields. There was hardly a garden in Lympstone where the footprints were not observed. The track appeared more like a biped than a quadroped, and the steps were generally eight inches in advance of each other. The impressions of the feet closely resembled that of a donkey's shoe.&quot;<br><br>So, what was it that left the winding trail of U shaped prints through uninterupted miles of the English countryside that snowy February morning? The prints were eventually found to have stretched for over one hundred miles and at one point jumped over a two mile wide river bank before picking up uninterrupted on the other side. It seems that nothing impeeded their progress across the countryside: they were found on each side of a haystack which was untouched; and on each side of a fourteen foot wall. A curious aspect of the prints was that they were placed directly one in front of the other, as opposed to typical side-by-side fashion.<br><br>Did the Devil pay a visit to the English countryside in 1855, or are there stranger things still waiting to be discovered by modern mankind?<br><br>What do you think? <br> <br> <p><img src=http://jawjrfotofile.homestead.com/files/lilfirebox.gif><i><a href><font color=red><font size=2>There is no faith in anything so strong it can't be shattered by one moment's glimpse of something it doesn't allow for.</font></font></a></i><br><img src=http://jawjrfotofile.homestead.com/files/rainbow_laser.gif><br><a href=http://pub34.ezboard.com/biciclesandicebergs target="web"><img src=http://jawjrfotofile.home